Big O notation (or just "O") is a mathematical convention used to describe the growth rate of an algorithm or function. It's denoted by a capital letter followed by a lowercase letter, and it describes how much space an algorithm takes up as input grows.

For example, consider the following algorithm:

    function add(x, y) {
        return x + y;
    }

This algorithm has a linear growth rate - that means its running time increases linearly with respect to both the size of the inputs. This can be written in Big O notation as follows:

    add(n, m) = O(n + m)

In this case, "O" represents the upper bound on the running time, which is proportional to n plus m. In other words, if we double either side of the equation, then the running time will increase by twice as much. Similarly, if we halve one side, then the running time will decrease by half as much.

So the key idea behind Big O notation is to express the relationship between two functions' running times without having to keep track of every detail of their implementation. By doing so, you can focus on understanding the overall behavior of your program rather than worrying about individual operations.

As for why mathematicians use Big O notation, it comes from computer science where it was first introduced. It's now widely accepted across many fields because it provides a clear way to compare algorithms and functions, regardless of their specific implementations. So whether you're writing code for computers, analyzing data sets, or solving problems in math class, using Big O notation can help you understand what's going on and make informed decisions.<|endoftext|>

